<subSubSection id="DE3B6532DEB5CD56D63979731D2503D4" pageId="6" pageNumber="21" type="distribution and habitat">
<paragraph id="8F63C820E54FDEE915C60E7716E443A5" pageId="6" pageNumber="21">Distribution and habitat.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="9F28AB15CA1FE6B668538DCCCA13AC1A" pageId="6" pageNumber="21">
This species is found from Central America and the Antilles through northern South America to the southern Amazon basin, in the Antilles, Belize, Bolivia, Brazil, Colombia, Costa Rica, Ecuador, French Guiana, Guatemala, Guyana, Honduras, Mexico, Panama, Peru, Surinam, and Venezuela, in different soil types and habitats (
<bibRefCitation id="2687F14171A7FC4AFA9AA4323DF10120" author="Lohmann, LG" journalOrPublisher="Annals of the Missouri Botanical Garden" pageId="8" pageNumber="23" pagination="348 - 489" refId="B11" refString="Lohmann, LG, Taylor, CM, 2014. A new generic classification of Bignonieae (Bignoniaceae) based on molecular phylogenetic data and morphological synapomorphies. Annals of the Missouri Botanical Garden 99 (3): 348 - 489" title="A new generic classification of Bignonieae (Bignoniaceae) based on molecular phylogenetic data and morphological synapomorphies." volume="99" year="2014">Lohmann and Taylor 2014</bibRefCitation>
; 
<figureCitation id="7A3CFD77BA7FDF2F0008D59D64776E3D" captionStart="Figure 3" captionStartId="F3" captionText="Figure 3. Distribution of Martinella species: Martinella insignis (solid blue circle), Martinella iquitoensis (solid green square) and Martinella obovata (open red triangles). Elevation in meters, according to the scale presented on the right." httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/10654" pageId="6" pageNumber="21">Fig. 3</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="D05682BF06ED16FA0FAC82444F271179" pageId="6" pageNumber="21" type="conservation status">
<paragraph id="1C48578EB984990DAEF101D2F11FEC53" pageId="6" pageNumber="21">Conservation status.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="941C0D66A3D153EEB5ECA91B1B917E27" pageId="6" pageNumber="21">
<taxonomicName id="CFBBD5F5576DE918969E88E16E17DD38" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Martinella" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Coleoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="21" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="obovata">
<emphasis id="35C5BDF58459614F215CF214240880C4" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="21">Martinella obovata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is distributed geographically through an area that is ≥ 2000 km2, with &lt;20% of its known individuals occurring outside Protected Areas, and seventy-two 
<bibRefCitation id="8455A5596C8FF1165637B42EE458F3F6" author="Rapoport, EH" journalOrPublisher="Pergamon, New York, USA" pageId="8" pageNumber="23" refId="B15" refString="Rapoport, EH, 1982. Aerography: Geographical Strategies of Species. Pergamon, New York, USA" title="Aerography: Geographical Strategies of Species" year="1982">Rapoport (1982)</bibRefCitation>
sub-populations known to date. Therefore, this species is here considered as Least Concern [LC] according to the IUCN criteria (
<bibRefCitation id="7B92238CE86E6E2499C16A4046D6C0E6" author="IUCN," journalOrPublisher="IUCN, Gland, Switzerland and Cambridge, UK" pageId="7" pageNumber="22" refId="B6" refString="IUCN, , 2012. IUCN Red List Categories and Criteria: Version 3.1. IUCN, Gland, Switzerland and Cambridge, UK" title="IUCN Red List Categories and Criteria: Version 3.1" year="2012">IUCN 2012</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="7B47A5DC99BAECEA623E6763174D390C" author="IUCN Standards and Petitions Subcommittee," journalOrPublisher="IUCN, Gland, Switzerland and Cambridge, UK" pageId="7" pageNumber="22" publicationUrl="http://www.iucnredlist.org/documents/RedListGuidelines.pdf" refId="B7" refString="IUCN Standards and Petitions Subcommittee, , 2014. Guidelines for using the IUCN red list categories and criteria. Version 11., http://www.iucnredlist.org/documents/RedListGuidelines.pdf" title="Guidelines for using the IUCN red list categories and criteria. Version 11" url="http://www.iucnredlist.org/documents/RedListGuidelines.pdf" year="2014">IUCN Standards and Petitions Subcommittee 2014</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="69DF3D44CD55118A8C41C597D5D97CC3" lastPageId="7" lastPageNumber="22" pageId="6" pageNumber="21" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="541E10331CA2FED69765E8BF33021EC3" pageId="6" pageNumber="21">Discussion.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="6AA64C0A06EA6EECEEEA0D9CD635CD79" lastPageId="7" lastPageNumber="22" pageId="6" pageNumber="21">
This species is the most variable and has the largest distribution in the genus (Central America and Caribbean throughout Amazon basin). Such variation is 
<pageBreakToken id="901A396C852BE84FA9946D575A212155" pageId="7" pageNumber="22" start="start">product</pageBreakToken>
of its phenotypic plasticity and wide ecological range, and is responsible for making this species hard to be distinguished from 
<taxonomicName id="33CD9273EBD028F9A99C6F7F0177CA79" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Martinella" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Coleoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="22" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="iquitoensis">
<emphasis id="7D26959BADC603D1A718B27A2A89301E" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="22">Martinella iquitoensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(as discussed above). Nonetheless, this high variation may also be seen as an evidence of a species complex, in which case, additional studies would be needed. For a complete list of synonyms see 
<bibRefCitation id="77C3C5C9440C7FAC8A396264DBE8F61D" author="Gentry, AH" journalOrPublisher="University of Gothenburg, Stockholm" pageId="7" pageNumber="22" pagination="1 - 173" refId="B3" refString="Gentry, AH, 1977. Flora of Ecuador. University of Gothenburg, Stockholm: 1 - 173" title="Flora of Ecuador" year="1977">Gentry (1977)</bibRefCitation>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
